Parents can check on their children at any time, and stress situations with delayed picking up children from preschools away from their parents ’ workplaces are falling away.
Thus, parents use their working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is a naturally loyal relationship between an employee and an employer.
Arch.Design thus joined Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are friendly to the family and through this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones fascinates after 100 years. Check the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the Casa Batlló house in Barcelona from the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudi.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned its nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all of which are typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The façade of the house plays dream lines, tender colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
The detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm, and precise order.
At night, the whole facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is lit so that the impression of the gloss of the colors is enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes appear equally in interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, eyes and rails.
The Batlló House, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Gràcia No. 43, was rebuilt in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, rich industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one, soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the apartment house Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created on his design board.
Many other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on Casa Batlló's designs started with successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá and Park Güell, where there are other Gaudí's works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion was earned thanks to its organic shapes the nickname "House of Bones".
Others began to call it a "deep house" because of a specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs include other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
Bizarre may seem to be their 45 - degree inclination.
In the creation of Gaudí, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of that time and did not allow them to bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the figures about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when finishing, the city council was destroyed and asked for correction.
The councillors, for example, resented the fact that the construction also interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
On the contrary, only 15 days after the challenge of the city district, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor was a social salon and on the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The whole six-story house crosses the staircase, which can be climbed to the roof terrace itself.
The fundamental elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and the larger society can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudí's reconstruction also gained unusual roofing and two additional floors in addition to the new facade.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which is lined with inner courtyard, and skylights, is also impressive.
The game of two colors gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was placed in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and luxurious apartment made available to the public.
The owners decided on this step only in 2002, on the occasion of celebrating the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed at the tours because they found that it was a very advantageous business and, moreover, they extended the tours with common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is EUR 16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20% discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you must quickly become friends with one of the residents and visit it directly at home.
