People watching machines want more and more parents, so they want to keep their children safe.
Fear for their own child brings more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
The system originally designed for the search for cars can also track the movement of people and thus help in cases such as the disappearance of 9-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be the size of a watch.
A lot of people got scared of the missing Anička case and started looking for means to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that it is not spying, but another means to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that in some cases such devices may be misused, such as when they are put in a bag to someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know the purpose of the box and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't want to wear anything like this, she'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose things when they don't want to be controlled."
"Great expectations had previously been triggered by mobile phones in parents, but they can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková said.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such equipment would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the kidnapping is concerned, the perpetrator will virtually always ensure that the child has no electronics on him that might reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When the tracking devices begin to expand, they will be looking for them, because their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In such a case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it admits that a similar device may help in the event of an emergency attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech, from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if there is immediate destruction of the tracking device after the attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set for regular positioning after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"The other devices have built-in tiltometers, so even if one slips and stays still, the device will send a warning immediately with a positioning," says Bohemia.
According to him, a similar service can be taken by smart mobile phones with navigation, where you can also upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to matchbox size pendants or smaller mobile phones.
It's always a threat to their loss.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, this is why the device now looks like a normal digital watch.
"It will have the greatest advantage that a possible aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he won't recognize them until after a while and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the tracking devices develop into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology that is used for car-sitting.
It is a combination of GPS tracking (which uses common self-navigation) and mobile phone functions that report the current position of the car.
