Longer index finger than ring finger indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than a ring finger are at less risk of becoming ill with prostate cancer.
This is a surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Magazine.
Could be related to the levels of male testosterone hormone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under 60," said Ros Eeles, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burdens, added Eeles.
In the period 1994-2009, more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and over three thousand healthy men followed with colleagues in Britain.
More than half of the study participants had a index finger on their right hand shorter than a ring finger.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those who had an index finger longer than a ring finger, the risk decreased by 33 percent, even 87 percent for men under the age of 60.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the various levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone matches the longer index finger.
Early research has shown that testosterone is supporting growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences Professor Václav Pačes told the Czech Press Agency that he knew about this study, but he does not seem to believe that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
