"This organism has a dual power."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic."
"This is a very strange fact, but it is not proof that it is a form of truly 'alien' life," commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of a report that appeared on Thursday in the online edition of Science magazine.
For a long time, six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur - have been considered essential for life.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced by arsenic.
"You will start to wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the news.
This finding is significant for searching for life outside the Earth, because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life may look like, said Anbar.
The study focuses on the microbes found on Earth.
However, the report on this news, published to discuss it, which did not reveal the details of the discovery, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That's not the case.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, Professor at Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows replacing one element with another element in the basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiological Institute at NASA, which conducted the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high arsenic levels.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, thus considering that microb, which is exposed to both elements, can be able to replace one after another.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"The result is that organisms can very hard to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it doesn't work. When it gets into the organism, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing arsenic concentrations, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better with phosphorus, but because they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility is increased that the life form that uses arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or on the moon, where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by phosphorus, was not new, but there was never an example on which this fact could be proved.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could be used by former life forms.
"This suggests that there could have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early period of the Earth," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
