On the contrary, it is another point in the complicated redefinition process of the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is supposed to be like, which is referring to the idea of observing old traditions, which is followed by a large part of the other members.
Faced with European opposition, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro area, which would include Germany, but also Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the mark - although it may now appear to be a science fiction, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option is, according to Germany's proposals, the reworking of the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary rigour, fines for the guilty states, possible deferrals for some of them, and the extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is now no room for spins.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission encouraged deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a discrepancy between what Germany considered correct (the fiscal rigour and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel painfully extended her decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of harsh criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion that was also published was strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October Merkel reappeared with a clear opinion, demanding to reform the European Union's conventions in order to enable the rescue of a Member State and at the same time allowing private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it has accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although in a somewhat moderate form, has been approved, and over the coming months we should follow the reform process of the Union, which should allow these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has set a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures are now needed, which it seems to disagree with too much, from that date, the old operation of the euro will be over.
The year 2013 will represent the birth of a new currency zone in which states breaking the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to declare deferment of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany suggests that we must take a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
They simply do not intend to tolerate another option based on debt and building, with huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed in the years of Spain’s growth boom.
