The tricks performed by Alonso and Ramos in the match with Ajax show the wit, not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League game against Ajax on November 23 caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is unsportsmanship and whether or not UEFA should punish both footballers.
As it is known, a few minutes before the end of the game (who had their team clearly won) appointed players one by one deliberately wasted time at the moment when the foul was to be played to provoke the judge, and he showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, both players will fulfill the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in the lead - and they will be able, free of cards, to continue to the next stage.
Finally, the Disciplinary Commission of UEFA gave coach José Mourinh a two-game penalty and the guilty players were fined in cash.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, that is, rules that are unwritten, but follow each other.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that its participant was Real Madrid (who boasts generosity and honour in his anthem, and who has already fined his player for similar actions), and it seems that the drama led by Mourinhem, which thus adds another episode to his long history of comedian and provocateur.
in any case, the debate revolves around whether this kind of action, which is not explicitly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is circumvention of the law in these acts; indeed, it is actions that respect sports rules, whose meaning seems to be trying to circumvent.
The type of damage such actions cause to the sports spirit is being addressed.
One aspect of sports behaviour is the physical integrity of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, so there was no violent play.
Another of these features characterizing a clean game is to avoid allowing players to have an advantage against the team because of their offense - which also did not happen here.
So the paradoxical thing about Real Madrid players’ action is that what we normally characterise as a ruse or circumvention of the law did not occur, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behavior should have been as obvious as possible in order to receive the punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
The next question, however, is what advantage guilty of their intentional transgressions will have.
It is necessary to state here that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position and that in the current match there is no advantage, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it's not even a useful strategy for the next game, because the club won't be able to count on these players.
The advantage is obviously that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, that is, at first glance, the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by doing so, players will be punished, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which one card less than the first round will be eliminated.
So as the wheels continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that allow maximum benefit under the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, players did not aim to avoid the granting of punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between ingenuity and circumvention of the rules is not clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly ingenuity.
It seems to me that controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusion and because of the way in which the instructions were transmitted to provoke them from the leadership.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
