The United States is amending the rules on issuing visas
People will have to contact the Centres of the Services for visa applicants before an interview at the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be shortened.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa consultation process at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Centres of the Services for Visa Applicants (abbreviated from English ASC) prior to an interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer a fee will be paid for the agreement of the meeting, the second for processing the application and more for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers’ visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to interview a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consulate Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra $26 service fee.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
NASA will announce the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The American Space Agency called for a press conference tomorrow to present a discovery that could cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life.
The United States National Aviation and Space Bureau (NASA) will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. by experts in astrobiology, science that deals with the study of origin, evolution, dissemination and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
When she invited journalists, NASA assured itself that she would present a "discovery that would cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life", arousing speculation by experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are, besides us, other creatures living under inhospitable conditions that have been considered uninhabitable, and who could represent the possibility that they will eventually become intelligent creatures, such as humans, if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Lake Mono in Yosemist National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too poisonous for any form of life, since the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic for its life, and it is this ability that increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have the atmosphere of what it is on Earth.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be shown that "there is another, second life form, different from the one we know."
The Space Agency will announce the true reach of discovery at tomorrow's press conference.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who examine Titan (the largest month of Saturn) with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that on Earth.
