World lighting recovery plan
Yesterday, in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan to restore home lighting, trade lighting and industrial space in 100 countries in order to achieve a greenhouse effect reduction (GES), which corresponds to almost one third of the other restrictions that need to be achieved for the stabilisation of the planet's climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult commitments to reduce on the part of industrialised countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, if the light bulbs that monopolize up to 50 to 70% of the market, we replace the light bulbs with fluocompact or, even better, with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet due to lighting would break off.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of the car park emissions on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe, and others, including Canada, were involved in voluntary reduction plans that should allow GES global emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract 5 Gt from this balance in order to achieve climate stabilisation at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 so that it can be ruled out that it will not get out of control.
In heated bulbs 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we will reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs can withstand an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, the ones that Philips introduced this week - this company allegedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated lifetime of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts expressed reservations about fluocompact light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be sorted as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, unless producers set up collection plants.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact bulb, but rather a thermal coal power plant that emits much mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, 25,000 tons of mercury per year are put into circulation by these headquarters.
The report also details the profits that any country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year to buy electricity and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to a 3.5 thermal power plant whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
