The rule that secret documents may consist only of news already known is fundamental in the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, Temples or Walls) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (he doesn't even know where to look for news about non-existent ones), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have learned before.
That's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
The same applies to classified documents.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited spirit) head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could, as I know, be an editor in Libération), who considers only what he admits to be true.
The high-security information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the State Department was the same information Newsweek published the week before.
Why, then, has there been so much fuss about the discovery of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that the embassy, at least since the end of World War II, and since the heads of state can make a call or take an airplane to a dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few little exercises in the representation, have transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer watching movies about an investigation knows very well that it seems to be ignored out of the least bit of laziness.
However, the fact that this is repeated publicly defamates the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most heavily classified information of the most powerful country in the world represents a hard blow, not an unmissable one, for the prestige of this state resort.
The scandal affects both the victims and his "executors".
But let's go from here to the deep truth about what happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, it was possible to hold all the power, like some Big Brother who controlled every move of his people.
Orvell's prophecy has been proven since, thanks to the ability to control every move through the phone, every transaction done, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, became a citizen of the complete victim of the wreath of power.
But when we demonstrate how it goes now, that even "graves" with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the hack's intervention, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker, elected to avenge a citizen, may know all the secrets of power.
How can he maintain a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that the real secret is an unencumbered secret (and an unencumbered secret will never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious, unencumbered secret, because it is pulled out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secret was an unencumbered secret, means taking away all power from it.
