Climate: how France hacked its promises on funding
A year after the Copenhagen agreement, it is time to test compliance with promises for quickly unblocked financing (said quick start funding or premature start funding), carried out by developed countries.
And the big French hacks have been exposed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries undertook to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has promised €7.2 billion for three years and France €1.26 billion (that is €420 million a year).
At the start of COP16, the EU drew a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report specifying the action of its Member States, press conference, grand side event, distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation priceless and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would want all developed countries and civil society to do them in the same way and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, bringing it on the right track to keep its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is realised without harming the development aid.
Unfortunately, there's no match for what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years to the title of fast start funding.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment dates or with dates at the level of public development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of public aid for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the overall amount of support from France to developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease) to honour its commitment to financing "new and additional"...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is not yet a rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that €1 borrowed equals €1 to be donated.
Clearly, it is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be evidenced for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reduction, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as equivalent to one euro that we give... , we should not see it as the basis of our commitments, but as the price of the loan for the creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only make such a statement: 'respects' its commitment of EUR 420 million, making it 91.5% loan (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document so that you can verify it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses a loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of it, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to satisfy its promise, France only gives 10 centimetres and considers this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful conjurer's piece!
To summarise, France operates with double fraud in its financing of fast start: on the one hand, with the development of the share over time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it only spends EUR 36.1 million, it can convince itself that it issues EUR 420 million 'new and additional' in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when it is enough to lend?) and when negotiating, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter on early funding is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to the series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope this isn't our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw on the findings of this first year of early funding.
First, France should notify the change in its way of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and decency and justice vis-à-vis other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing contributions to long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of 'additionality' or how to account for loans.
France should change its position in order to become as progressive with these deposits as with others.
So everyone is putting hope into the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Koscius-Morizet, who will be arriving in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could raise the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
